[normal]Written evidence submitted by Basf Plc (CCS01)[bold]The Committee invites responses addressing some or all of the following questions:
[normal]BASF intends to respond to those listed in red given our expertise and interest
[normal]s. 
[normal]BASF
[normal] is the world’s leading chemical co
[normal]mpany: The Chemical Company. Our
[normal] portfolio ranges from chemicals, plastics, performance products and crop protection products to oil and gas. We combine economic suc
[normal]cess with environmental protection and social responsibility. Through science and
[normal] innovation, we enable our customers in nearly every industry to meet the current and future needs of society. Our products and solutions contribute to conserving resources, e
[normal]nsuring nutrition and improving quality of life. We have summed up this contribution in our corporate purpose: We create chemistry for a sustainable future. BASF had sales of €72.1 billion in 2012 and more than 110,000 employees as of the end of the year. 
[normal]BASF has been at the forefront of innovation in gas treatment for over 40 years. In 1971, the company for the first time applied newly developed technology based on activated methyldiethanolamine to remove carbon dioxide (CO2) from synthesis 
[normal]gas to produce ammonia, a crucial starting material for fertilizer. The facility, which is still in operation, is located at the Ludwigshafen, Germany. 
[normal]Today, almost 300 plants worldwide employ BASF’s knowhow to remove acid gases such as CO2 and hydrogen 
[normal]sulphide (H2S) from various types of process gases. Recently, the company started marketing its combined gas treating technology, chemical and technical service offerings under the new Oase® brand. 
[normal]With climate change becoming an increasing concern global
[normal]ly, the team is actively leveraging its expertise to become a leading contender in the race to make carbon capture and storage (CCS) commercially viable. 
[normal]More information about BASF’s gas treatment solutions can be found here:
[normal]http://www.intermediates.basf.com/chemicals/web/gas-treatment/en/
[normal]BASF UK generated €3.6bn revenue in 2012 of which €1.9bn was oil, gas, and metals trading. Th
[normal]e remaining €1.7bn accounts for 3% of BASF global chemical sales (€62bn), Our UK mark
[normal]et share is around 3% of the £
[normal]57
[normal]bn 
[normal]UK 
[normal]Chemicals sector. 
[normal]The bulk of our UK sales are chemicals and performance products (e.g. pigments, water treatments and care chemical
[normal]s). We are major providers 
[normal]of product 
[normal]to supply chains for 
[normal]oil and gas, 
[normal]agriculture, automotive, construction, and pharmaceuticals, as well as to other chemical manufacturers. 
[normal]We are major sponsor of innovation in the UK with over 100 R&amp;D partnerships in 
[normal]2011. Within BASF this was the highest number outside Germany. These range from
[normal] university projects with partners such as Imperial College, to institutional projects and
[normal] commercial partnerships with BP and Shell.
[normal]If we were a UK-led business we would be on
[normal]e of the top 100 companies in the UK. Several of our sites have over 80% of their product exported.
[normal] We are one of @70 companies engaging with the Government’s Strategic Relationship Management Programme
