[normal]Niederaussem[bold] – solvents for scrubbing [bold]BASF
[normal] is a partner in a pilot project st
[normal]eered by RWE Power at 
[normal]the
[normal] Coal Innovation 
[normal]Centre
[normal] in Niederaussem, Germany, near Cologne. The object is to test highly energy-efficient and oxygen-stable solvents for removing carbon dioxide from bituminous coal emissions. BASF has developed an improved scr
[normal]ubbing process
[normal], based on
[normal] 
[normal]innovative 
[normal]solvents
[normal], 
[normal]to capture CO
[normal]2
[normal]. We have
[normal] demonstrated that energy input can be slashed by about 20%.
[normal]The pilot plant was built and engineered by Munich-based inte
[normal]rnational gases group Linde. It 
[normal]captures around eight tonnes per 
[normal]day of CO
[normal]2
[normal], equivalent to a separation efficiency of 90% for the flue gas processed. The technology should allow more than 90% of the process gas from a power plant to be captured for sequestration underground. 
[normal]Both BASF and Linde are now working on solut
[normal]ions for demonstration plants – the first are due on stream in 2015 – as well as large-scale power plants. CO
[normal]2
[normal] capture is expected to be used commercially
[normal] in coal-fired power stations in
[normal] 2020. 
[normal]Puertollano – IGCC output purification[bold]In Spain
[normal] a special BASF gas treatment technology
[normal] 
[normal]- similar to the purification of syngas - is being used at the IGCC (Integrated Gasification Combined Cycle) power plant of ELCOGAS in Puertollano
[normal]. It
[normal] 
[normal]will
[normal] capture about 35,000 tons of gas annually. The plant
[normal],
[normal] alrea
[normal]dy in commercial-scale operation, is also being used for demonstration purposes. It is expected to provide a wealth of information relating to the viability of the IGCC concept, which differs from the post-combustion capture concept. 
[normal]North Carolina – seco[bold]nd generation ‘water-free’ capture technology[bold]In the US BASF has joined forces with RTI International – a
[normal]n institute 
[normal]bas
[normal]ed in Research Triangle Park, 
[normal]North Carolina – to develop second-generation capture technology. 
[normal]We
[normal] 
[normal]are looking
[normal] into novel non-aqueous so
[normal]lvent systems that can be recycled. The aim is to find a “water free” capture process that could use 40% less energy than conventional amine-based processes.
[normal]We hope to
[normal] clear a path for rapid commercialisation of the carbon capture technology and thus enab
[normal]le cost-competitive clean energy production from coal-fired power plants.
[normal]Nagaoka City – efficient CO[bold]2[bold] recovery from natural gas[bold]In Japan, BASF has linked up with local companies JGC and INPEX to perform demonstration tests with a new technology for effect
[normal]ively capturing and recovering CO
[normal]2
[normal] contained in natural gas. The tests were started in August 2010 at INPEX’s Koshijihara natural gas plant in Nagaoka City.
[normal]JGC and BASF in began developing the High Pressure Acid Gas Capture Technology (HiPACT) in 2004. Th
[normal]is process shows a “significantly higher” CO
[normal]2
[normal] absorption, compared with existing processes, and is capable of regenerating the solvent under high pressure conditions. An important milestone will be to transfer the new technology to an operating gas process
[normal]ing plant.
[normal]HiPACT should help reduce overall power consumption in the facility while also lowering investment costs. 
[normal]B
[normal]ecause the gas is released from the solvent at well above atmospheric pressure there is
[normal] also 
[normal] a significant reduction in the amount of ene
[normal]rgy required 
[normal]for
[normal] high pressure applications such as chemical synthesis or underground
[normal] sequestration
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]W
[normal]e would not be involved in
[normal] pilot projects if we did not believe carbon capture technologies were likely to present significant commerci
[normal]al opportunities in future. For example
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]in 
[normal]the Middle East demand for purified CO2 is increasing, in particular to raise yields in crude oil production (by means of enhanced oil recovery) and in urea production.
[normal]There are and will be markets for Carbon Ca
[normal]pture technologies even if Carbon Capture and Storage proves to be an unworkable or uneconomic choice for climate change mitigation. 
[normal]CCS is still 
[normal]a 
[normal]very expensive 
[normal]and unproven 
[normal]way to mitigate 
[normal]CO
[normal]2
[normal] emissions from industrial processes and generation. It reduces efficiency and productivity compared to processes without CCS. It is some way from being cost competitive with the best alternative carbon reduction technologies. 
[normal]At the current time, without
[normal] a 
[normal]comparable  
[normal]global price for the carbon,
[normal] the introduction of CCS
[normal] within the UK or EU unilaterally,
[normal] would lead
[normal] to higher energy bills for domestic consumers and 
[normal]competitive disadvantage
[normal]s
[normal] for industry
[normal]. This would be true for 
[normal]both 
[normal]energy-intensive industry
[normal] (due to higher e
[normal]lectricity prices) and for carbon-intensive
[normal] industry
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]that would have to introduce
[normal] their own CCS
[normal])
[normal].
[normal]Nevertheless, 
[normal]if there were a global price for carbon
[normal],
[normal] CCS
[normal] might have advantages:
[normal]Policy measures 
[normal]to 
[normal]encourage
[normal] CCS in 
[normal]the UK and EU
[normal] should not seek to put a 
[normal]high cost burden on 
[normal]domestic 
[normal]c
[normal]ompanies 
[normal]and consumers
[normal]. 
[normal]T
[normal]hey
[normal] should 
[normal]focus on 
[normal]the development and demonstration 
[normal]of 
[normal]future 
[normal](and lower cost) 
[normal]CCS technology thro
[normal]ugh targeted fundin
[normal]g, rather than
[normal] deployment 
[normal]subsidies. 
[normal]If UK CCS demonstrations are generously subsidised, and UK industry is forced to pay for this through electricity market reform and / or inadequate energy intensive industry exemptions - one clear consequence is that manufacturing suppliers to CCS projects
[normal] based in the UK will be less competitive than those not paying the subsidies outside the UK. 
[normal]Support for CCS, like other low carbon technologies carries a strong risk of creating a ‘green growth paradox’. Making a market but unmaking the domestic industr
[normal]y required to service it. 
[normal]Publi
[normal]c finance 
[normal]for R&amp;D 
[normal]is 
[normal]though 
[normal]essential for CCS. 
[normal]Private investors alone will not take on the risk of a technology that has no market without significant sustained government intervention to create one.  
[normal]Public subsidies are o
[normal]nly acceptable for the pilot phase of new technologies and have to be reduced according to the cost reduction. Long
[normal]er 
[normal]term 
[normal]subsidies which have to be paid
[normal] by other market participants are not acceptable.
[normal]S
[normal]ocial acceptance is 
[normal]crucial
[normal]. The extensive developm
[normal]ent and operation of appropri
[normal]ate sites and
[normal] a nationwide network of pipelines 
[normal]will require 
[normal]dialogue with the public and NGOs.
[normal] 
[normal]A single
[normal] legal 
[normal]framework is also helpful
[normal]. Regional
[normal] variation
[normal] - as in Germ
[normal]any - has led to some states blocking pilots. 
[normal]Technology 
[normal]nationalism will not help deliver CCS. It is unlikely any one country will have comparative a
[normal]dvantage in every aspect of the 
[normal]CCS value
[normal] chain.  CCS
[normal] expertise is global.  Our spread of projects in the EU, US and Asia we hope demonstrate
[normal]s
[normal] the benefits 
[normal]and spr
[normal]ead 
[normal]of multilateral partnerships. 
[normal] 
[normal]We, or rather our Wingas Storage subsidiary at Saltfleetby (currently in transition to Gazprom subject to a Commission competition ruling), have already found the UK market for storage solutions to be challenging. 
