[normal],
[normal] not helped the commercialisation and export of ‘invented here’ technologies. 
[normal]We suspect
[normal] further
[normal] there has been less ‘invented here’ as a result of seeking UK-led projects rather than partnerships of the willing. 
[normal]These c
[normal]ould lower UK costs
[normal],
[normal] while broadeni
[normal]n
[normal]g the pool of  expertise involved, and improving the prospects for future commercial success. 
[normal]For example, for the
[normal] manufacture of BASF’s future CCS intermediates to take place in the UK, even those based on 
[normal]hypothetical 
[normal]UK science partnerships, there wou
[normal]ld have to be significant evidence of comparative advantage from the tax, planning and regulatory regime, local expertise, and appropriate sites. 
[normal]We would need to see evidence of an emerging CCS hub both domestic and for export, and multiple partners
[normal],
[normal] to 
[normal]spread risk and accelerate innovation. We would like
[normal]ly
[normal] seek to invest in and partner with emerging SMEs or adapt existing plant rather than build from scratch. 
[normal]All of this would need 
[normal]to be significantly and relatively more attractive than current opportunities in other countries - many of which are ahead of the UK in respect of CCS projects and pilots – many of which have established cost advantages for skills and supply in Intermediat
[normal]e Chemicals. 
[normal]We do agree with the strong focus in the strategy placed on cost-reduction. We do agree with many of the 
[normal]ideas put forward by the report
[normal] of the CCS Cost Reduction Task Force. We do again though think too much attention is being given to domes
[normal]tic pilots and projects and not enough to selecting markets and partners with lower cost profiles than t
[normal]he UK. 
